Here's how to handle all three requirements:

**1 & 2 — Intercept back navigation + confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page code-behind to catch the hardware/Android back button:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget; return true to cancel navigation immediately
        ConfirmDiscardAsync();
        return true; // cancels default back navigation
    }

    private async Task ConfirmDiscardAsync()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, use `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` to replace the arrow with a "Cancel" button that runs the same logic:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (!HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            return;
        }

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **hardware/system** back button (mainly Android).
- `BackButtonBehavior` handles the **Shell toolbar** back button and lets you customize its text/icon.
- You need both — they cover different back-navigation paths.
